{"author":{"id":"b78c39e7b13f90a5827abfba043255fe7a4ede1499df23f110fffe5abfa44adc"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1772110906,"nonce":"gB8d1AOnrHG4dVgTs3XNYaUuC3Y=","metadata":{"github-id":"I_kwDOQ241x87uJT9L","github-url":"https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/268","origin":"github"},"title":"Add guiding principle: human control and transparency","message":"## Summary\n\nAdd a new guiding principle to `docs/PRINCIPLES.md` addressing human control and transparency.\n\n## Motivation\n\nThe workspace has extensive mechanisms for control and visibility — autonomy boundaries in AGENTS.md, draft PR workflows, AI signatures, issue-first policy — but no guiding principle explicitly articulates *why* these exist or what they serve. Elevating this to a principle makes the intent clear and provides review criteria for future changes.\n\n## Proposed Principle\n\n\u003e **Human control and transparency**\n\u003e\n\u003e The user must be able to understand what an agent is doing, how it is\n\u003e doing it, and why it chose that approach. This transparency is the\n\u003e foundation for trust — and trust is what earns agents greater autonomy.\n\u003e Design controls to be configurable: tight by default, relaxable as\n\u003e confidence grows.\n\nKey aspects:\n- **Configurable control**: human oversight should be tunable — tight by default, relaxable as trust is built\n- **Transparency enables trust**: to build confidence, it must be easy for the user to understand:\n  - **What** an agent is doing\n  - **How** it is doing it\n  - **Why** it chose that approach\n- The principle should be unnumbered (remove numbering from the existing principles as well, or add it without a number)\n\n## Scope\n\n- Update `docs/PRINCIPLES.md`\n- Consider whether existing numbered principles should be converted to unnumbered to match\n\n---\n**Authored-By**: `Claude Code Agent`\n**Model**: `Claude Opus 4.6`","files":null}]}